The paper focuses on using web search engine interactions as a means of measuring cognitive performance and correlating it with wearable device-defined sleep measures. This suggests a focus on cybernetics (cs.CY) and human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The study also involves statistical modeling (cs.SI) and information retrieval (cs.IR) techniques to analyze the data. Finally, the paper discusses the feasibility of using online interactions for large-scale physiological sensing, which could fall under the category of machine learning (cs.LG).
